# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lxml-xml
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] A **document type definition** (**DTD**) is a specification file that contains a set of *markup declarations* that define a *document type* for an SGML-family markup language (GML, SGML, XML, HTML).
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] The DTD specification file can be used to validate documents.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] A DTD defines the valid building blocks of an XML document.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] It defines the document structure with a list of validated elements and attributes.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] A DTD can be declared inline inside an XML document, or as an external reference.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] DTDs persist in applications that need special publishing characters, such as the XML and HTML Character Entity References, which derive from larger sets defined as part of the ISO SGML standard effort.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] An attempt to create namespace-aware DTDs was being developed as Part 9 of ISO DSDL, but this was ultimately withdrawn.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] As of 2009, newer XML namespace-aware schema languages (such as W3C XML Schema and ISO RELAX NG) have largely superseded DTDs as a better way to validate XML structure.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] A DTD is associated with an XML or SGML document by means of a document type declaration (DOCTYPE).
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] The DOCTYPE appears in the syntactic fragment *doctypedecl* near the start of an XML document.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] The declaration establishes that the document is an instance of the type defined by the referenced DTD.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] The declarations in the internal subset form part of the DOCTYPE in the document itself.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] The declarations in the external subset are located in a separate text file.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] The external subset may be referenced via a *public identifier* and/or a *system identifier*.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] Programs for reading documents may not be required to read the external subset.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] However, such documents are still fully parsable in the *non*-standalone mode of validating parsers, which signals an error if it can not locate these external entities with their specified *public identifier* (FPI) or *system identifier* (a URI), or are inaccessible.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] Non-validating parsers *may* eventually attempt to locate these external entities in the *non*-standalone mode (by partially interpreting the DTD only to resolve their declared parsable entities), but do not validate the content model of these documents.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] All HTML 4.01 documents conform to one of three SGML DTDs.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] The system identifiers of these DTDs, if present in the DOCTYPE, are URI references.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] A system identifier usually points to a specific set of declarations in a resolvable location.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] SGML allows mapping public identifiers to system identifiers in catalogs that are optionally available to the URI resolvers used by document parsing software.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] This DOCTYPE can only appear *after* the optional XML declaration, and before the document body, if the document syntax conforms to XML.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] DTDs describe the structure of a class of documents via element and attribute-list declarations.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] Element declarations name the allowable set of elements within the document, and specify whether and how declared elements and runs of character data may be contained within each element.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] Attribute-list declarations name the allowable set of attributes for each declared element, including the type of each attribute value, if not an explicit set of valid values.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] DTD markup declarations declare which element types, attribute lists, entities, and notations are allowed in the structure of the corresponding class of XML documents.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] An element type declaration defines an element and its possible content.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] A valid XML document contains only elements that are defined in the DTD.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] Element type declarations are ignored by *non-validating* SGML and XML parsers (in which cases, any elements are accepted in any order, and in any number of occurrences in the parsed document), but these declarations are still checked for form and validity.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] An attribute list specifies for a given element type the list of all possible attribute associated with that type.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] " with this type, without needing any declaration in the DTD, so the uniqueness constraint also applies to these defined identifiers when they are specified anywhere in a XML document.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] " pipe character) of notation names, where each notation name in the enumeration must also be declared in the document type declaration; this type is not supported in HTML parsers, but is valid in SGML and XML 1.0 or 1.1 (including XHTML and SVG).
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] A default value can define whether an attribute must occur (`#REQUIRED`) or not (`#IMPLIED`), or whether it has a fixed value (`#FIXED`), or which value should be used as a default value ("…") in case the given attribute is left out in an XML tag.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] Attribute list declarations are ignored by *non-validating* SGML and XML parsers (in which cases any attribute is accepted within all elements of the parsed document), but these declarations are still checked for well-formedness and validity.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] The entity declaration assigns it a value that is retained throughout the document.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] A common use is to have a name more recognizable than a numeric character reference for an unfamiliar character.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] Entities help to improve legibility of an XML text.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] In general, there are two types: internal and external.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] Reference to the "author" internal entity is not substituted in the replacement text of the "signature" internal entity.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] The "%" character for introducing parameter entity references in the DTD loses its special role outside the DTD and it becomes a literal character.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] However, the references to predefined character entities are substituted wherever they occur, without needing a validating parser (they are only introduced by the "&" character).
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] They provide a complete reference to unparsed external entities whose interpretation is left to the application (which interprets them directly or retrieves the external entity themselves), by assigning them a simple name, which is usable in the body of the document.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] For example, notations may be used to reference non-XML data in an XML 1.1 document.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] This declares the Media Type of external images with this type, and associates it with a notation name "type-image-svg".
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] The declared notation name must be unique within all the document type declaration, i.e. in the external subset as well as the internal subset, at least for conformance with XML.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] Notations can be associated to unparsed external entities included in the body of the SGML or XML document.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] The `PUBLIC` or `SYSTEM` parameter of these external entities specifies the FPI and/or the URI where the unparsed data of the external entity is located, and the additional `NDATA` parameter of these defined entities specifies the additional notation (i.e., effectively the MIME type here).
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] Notations may also be associated directly to elements as additional meta-data, without associating them to another external entity, by giving their names as possible values of some additional attributes (also declared in the DTD within the `<!ATTLIST ...>` declaration of the element).
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] The example above shows a notation named "type-image-svg" that references the standard public FPI and the system identifier (the standard URI) of an SVG 1.1 document, instead of specifying just a system identifier as in the first example (which was a relative URI interpreted locally as a MIME type).
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] This annotation is referenced directly within the unparsed "type" attribute of the "img" element, but its content is not retrieved.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] It also declares another notation for a vendor-specific application, to annotate the "sgml" root element in the document.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] In both cases, the declared notation named is used directly in a declared "type" attribute, whose content is specified in the DTD with the "NOTATION" attribute type (this "type" attribute is declared for the "sgml" element, as well as for the "img" element).
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] However, the "title" attribute of the "img" element specifies the internal entity "example1SVGTitle" whose declaration that does not define an annotation, so it is parsed by validating parsers and the entity replacement text is "Title of example1.svg".
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] The effective content for the "img" element be the content of this second external resource.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] Only one notation name may be specified in the value of ENTITY attributes (there is no support in SGML, XML 1.0 or XML 1.1 for multiple notation names in the same declared external ENTITY, so separate attributes are needed).
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] However multiple external entities may be referenced (in a space-separated list of names) in attributes declared with type ENTITIES, and where each named external entity is also declared with its own notation).
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] Notations are also completely opaque for XML and SGML parsers, so they are not differentiated by the type of the external entity that they may reference (for these parsers they just have a unique name associated to a public identifier (an FPI) and/or a system identifier (a URI)).
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] Some applications (but not XML or SGML parsers themselves) also allow referencing notations indirectly by naming them in the `"URN:''name''"` value of a standard CDATA attribute, everywhere a URI can be specified.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] However this behaviour is application-specific, and requires that the application maintains a catalog of known URNs to resolve them into the notations that have been parsed in a standard SGML or XML parser.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] This use allows notations to be defined only in a DTD stored as an external entity and referenced only as the external subset of documents, and allows these documents to remain compatible with validating XML or SGML parsers that have no direct support for notations.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] Even in validating SGML or XML 1.0 or XML 1.1 parsers, the external entities referenced by an FPI and/or URI in declared notations are not retrieved automatically by the parsers themselves.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] The XML DTD syntax is one of several XML schema languages.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] However, many of the schema languages do not fully replace the XML DTD.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] Most XML schema languages are only replacements for element declarations and attribute list declarations, in such a way that it becomes possible to parse XML documents with *non-validating* XML parsers (if the only purpose of the external DTD subset was to define the schema).
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] A *non-validating* parser may, however, elect not to read parsable *external entities* (including the *external subset*), and does not have to honor the content model restrictions defined in element declarations and in attribute list declarations.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] If the XML document depends on parsable external entities (including the specified *external subset*, or parsable external entities declared in the *internal subset*), it should assert `standalone="no"` in its XML declaration.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] The validating DTD may be identified by using XML Catalogs to retrieve its specified *external subset*.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] If it just includes any PUBLIC identifier, it *may* be processed as standalone, if the XML processor knows this PUBLIC identifier in its local catalog from where it can retrieve an associated DTD entity.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] `person` is a valid element name, and an instance of such an element contains one element named `name`, followed by one named `birthdate` (optional), then `gender` (also optional) and `socialsecuritynumber` (also optional).
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] The `?` indicates that an element is optional.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] The reference to the `name` element name has no `?`, so a `person` element *must* contain a `name` element.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] `name` is a valid element name, and an instance of such an element contains "parsed character data" (#PCDATA).
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] `birthdate` is a valid element name, and an instance of such an element contains parsed character data.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] `gender` is a valid element name, and an instance of such an element contains parsed character data.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] `socialsecuritynumber` is a valid element name, and an instance of such an element contains parsed character data.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] An example of an XML file that uses and conforms to this DTD follows.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] The DTD is referenced here as an external subset, via the SYSTEM specifier and a URI.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] One can render this in an XML-enabled browser (such as Internet Explorer or Mozilla Firefox) by pasting and saving the DTD component above to a text file named *example.dtd* and the XML file to a differently-named text file, and opening the XML file with the browser.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] The files should both be saved in the same directory.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] However, many browsers do not check that an XML document confirms to the rules in the DTD; they are only required to check that the DTD is syntactically correct.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] For security reasons, they may also choose not to read the external DTD.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] An XML DTD can be used to create a Denial-of-service attack by defining nested entities that expand exponentially, or by sending the XML parser to an external resource that never returns.
[src:lxml-xml/document-type-definition] For this reason, .NET Framework provides a property that allows prohibiting or skipping DTD parsing, and recent versions of Microsoft Office applications (Microsoft Office 2010 and higher) refuse to open XML files that contain DTD declarations.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The term has slightly different meanings in different branches of linguistics and computer science.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Traditional sentence parsing is often performed as a method of understanding the exact meaning of a sentence or word, sometimes with the aid of devices such as sentence diagrams.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] It usually emphasizes the importance of grammatical divisions such as subject and predicate.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Within computational linguistics the term is used to refer to the formal analysis by a computer of a sentence or other string of words into its constituents, resulting in a parse tree showing their syntactic relation to each other, which may also contain semantic information.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Some parsing algorithms generate a *parse forest* or list of parse trees from a string that is syntactically ambiguous.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The term is also used in psycholinguistics when describing language comprehension.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Within computer science, the term is used in the analysis of computer languages, referring to the syntactic analysis of the input code into its component parts in order to facilitate the writing of compilers and interpreters.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The term may also be used to describe a split or separation.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] In data analysis, the term is often used to refer to a process extracting desired information from data, e.g., creating a time series signal from a XML document.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The traditional grammatical exercise of parsing, sometimes known as *clause analysis*, involves breaking down a text into its component parts of speech with an explanation of the form, function, and syntactic relationship of each part.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] This is determined in large part from study of the language's conjugations and declensions, which can be quite intricate for heavily inflected languages.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] To parse a phrase such as "man bites dog" involves noting that the singular noun "man" is the subject of the sentence, the verb "bites" is the third person singular of the present tense of the verb "to bite", and the singular noun "dog" is the object of the sentence.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Techniques such as sentence diagrams are sometimes used to indicate relation between elements in the sentence.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Parsing was formerly central to the teaching of grammar throughout the English-speaking world, and widely regarded as basic to the use and understanding of written language.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] In some machine translation and natural language processing systems, written texts in human languages are parsed by computer programs.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Human sentences are not easily parsed by programs, as there is substantial ambiguity in the structure of human language, whose usage is to convey meaning (or semantics) amongst a potentially unlimited range of possibilities, but only some of which are germane to the particular case.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] So an utterance "Man bites dog" versus "Dog bites man" is definite on one detail but in another language might appear as "Man dog bites" with a reliance on the larger context to distinguish between those two possibilities, if indeed that difference was of concern.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] It is difficult to prepare formal rules to describe informal behaviour even though it is clear that some rules are being followed.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] In order to parse natural language data, researchers must first agree on the grammar to be used.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The choice of syntax is affected by both linguistic and computational concerns; for instance some parsing systems use lexical functional grammar, but in general, parsing for grammars of this type is known to be NP-complete.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Head-driven phrase structure grammar is another linguistic formalism which has been popular in the parsing community, but other research efforts have focused on less complex formalisms such as the one used in the Penn Treebank.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Shallow parsing aims to find only the boundaries of major constituents such as noun phrases.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Another popular strategy for avoiding linguistic controversy is dependency grammar parsing.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Most modern parsers are at least partly statistical; that is, they rely on a corpus of training data which has already been annotated (parsed by hand).
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] This approach allows the system to gather information about the frequency with which various constructions occur in specific contexts.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] *(See machine learning.)* Approaches which have been used include straightforward PCFGs (probabilistic context-free grammars), maximum entropy, and neural nets.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Most of the more successful systems use *lexical* statistics (that is, they consider the identities of the words involved, as well as their part of speech).
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] However such systems are vulnerable to overfitting and require some kind of smoothing to be effective.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Parsing algorithms for natural language cannot rely on the grammar having 'nice' properties as with manually designed grammars for programming languages.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] As mentioned earlier some grammar formalisms are very difficult to parse computationally; in general, even if the desired structure is not context-free, some kind of context-free approximation to the grammar is used to perform a first pass.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Algorithms which use context-free grammars often rely on some variant of the CYK algorithm, usually with some heuristic to prune away unlikely analyses to save time.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] *(See chart parsing.)* However some systems trade speed for accuracy using, e.g., linear-time versions of the shift-reduce algorithm.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] A somewhat recent development has been parse reranking in which the parser proposes some large number of analyses, and a more complex system selects the best option.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] In natural language understanding applications, semantic parsers convert the text into a representation of its meaning.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] In psycholinguistics, parsing involves not just the assignment of words to categories (formation of ontological insights), but the evaluation of the meaning of a sentence according to the rules of syntax drawn by inferences made from each word in the sentence (known as connotation).
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] This normally occurs as words are being heard or read.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Neurolinguistics generally understands parsing to be a function of working memory, meaning that parsing is used to keep several parts of one sentence at play in the mind at one time, all readily accessible to be analyzed as needed.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Because the human working memory has limitations, so does the function of sentence parsing.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] This is evidenced by several different types of syntactically complex sentences that demonstrate potential issues for mental parsing of sentences.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The first, and perhaps most well-known, type of sentence that challenges parsing ability is the garden-path sentence.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] These sentences are designed so that the most common interpretation of the sentence appears grammatically faulty, but upon further inspection, these sentences are grammatically sound.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Garden-path sentences are difficult to parse because they contain a phrase or a word with more than one meaning, often their most typical meaning being a different part of speech.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] For example, in the sentence, "the horse raced past the barn fell", raced is initially interpreted as a past tense verb, but in this sentence, it functions as part of an adjective phrase.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Since parsing is used to identify parts of speech, these sentences challenge the parsing ability of the reader.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Another type of sentence that is difficult to parse is an attachment ambiguity, which includes a phrase that could potentially modify different parts of a sentence, and therefore presents a challenge in identifying syntactic relationship (i.e.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] A third type of sentence that challenges parsing ability is center embedding, in which phrases are placed in the center of other similarly formed phrases (i.e.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] "The rat the cat the man hit chased ran into the trap".) Sentences with 2 or in the most extreme cases 3 center embeddings are challenging for mental parsing, again because of ambiguity of syntactic relationship.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Within neurolinguistics there are multiple theories that aim to describe how parsing takes place in the brain.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The opposing, more contemporary model theorizes that within the mind, the processing of a sentence is not modular, or happening in strict sequence.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Rather, it poses that several different syntactic possibilities can be considered at the same time, because lexical access, syntactic processing, and determination of meaning occur in parallel in the brain.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] In this way these processes are integrated.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Although there is still much to learn about the neurology of parsing, studies have shown evidence that several areas of the brain might play a role in parsing.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] These include the left anterior temporal pole, the left inferior frontal gyrus, the left superior temporal gyrus, the left superior frontal gyrus, the right posterior cingulate cortex, and the left angular gyrus.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Although it has not been absolutely proven, it has been suggested that these different structures might favor either phrase-structure parsing or dependency-structure parsing, meaning different types of parsing could be processed in different ways which have yet to be understood.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Discourse analysis examines ways to analyze language use and semiotic events.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Persuasive language may be called rhetoric.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] A **parser** is a software component that takes input data (typically text) and builds a data structure – often some kind of parse tree, abstract syntax tree or other hierarchical structure, giving a structural representation of the input while checking for correct syntax.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The parsing may be preceded or followed by other steps, or these may be combined into a single step.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The parser is often preceded by a separate lexical analyser, which creates tokens from the sequence of input characters; alternatively, these can be combined in scannerless parsing.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Parsers may be programmed by hand or may be automatically or semi-automatically generated by a parser generator.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Parsing is complementary to templating, which produces formatted *output.* These may be applied to different domains, but often appear together, such as the scanf/printf pair, or the input (front end parsing) and output (back end code generation) stages of a compiler.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The input to a parser is typically text in some computer language, but may also be text in a natural language or less structured textual data, in which case generally only certain parts of the text are extracted, rather than a parse tree being constructed.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Parsers range from very simple functions such as scanf, to complex programs such as the frontend of a C++ compiler or the HTML parser of a web browser.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] An important class of simple parsing is done using regular expressions, in which a group of regular expressions defines a regular language and a regular expression engine automatically generating a parser for that language, allowing pattern matching and extraction of text.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] In other contexts regular expressions are instead used prior to parsing, as the lexing step whose output is then used by the parser.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] In the case of data languages, a parser is often found as the file reading facility of a program, such as reading in HTML or XML text; these examples are markup languages.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] In the case of programming languages, a parser is a component of a compiler or interpreter, which parses the source code of a computer programming language to create some form of internal representation; the parser is a key step in the compiler frontend.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Programming languages tend to be specified in terms of a deterministic context-free grammar because fast and efficient parsers can be written for them.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] For compilers, the parsing itself can be done in one pass or multiple passes – see one-pass compiler and multi-pass compiler.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The implied disadvantages of a one-pass compiler can largely be overcome by adding fix-ups, where provision is made for code relocation during the forward pass, and the fix-ups are applied backwards when the current program segment has been recognized as having been completed.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] An example where such a fix-up mechanism would be useful would be a forward GOTO statement, where the target of the GOTO is unknown until the program segment is completed.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] In this case, the application of the fix-up would be delayed until the target of the GOTO was recognized.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Conversely, a backward GOTO does not require a fix-up, as the location will already be known.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Context-free grammars are limited in the extent to which they can express all of the requirements of a language.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Informally, the reason is that the memory of such a language is limited.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The grammar cannot remember the presence of a construct over an arbitrarily long input; this is necessary for a language in which, for example, a name must be declared before it may be referenced.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] More powerful grammars that can express this constraint, however, cannot be parsed efficiently.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Thus, it is a common strategy to create a relaxed parser for a context-free grammar which accepts a superset of the desired language constructs (that is, it accepts some invalid constructs); later, the unwanted constructs can be filtered out at the semantic analysis (contextual analysis) step.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The following example demonstrates the common case of parsing a computer language with two levels of grammar: lexical and syntactic.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The first stage is the token generation, or lexical analysis, by which the input character stream is split into meaningful symbols defined by a grammar of regular expressions.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] For example, a calculator program would look at an input such as "`12 * (3 + 4)^2`" and split it into the tokens `12`, `*`, `(`, `3`, `+`, `4`, `)`, `^`, `2`, each of which is a meaningful symbol in the context of an arithmetic expression.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The lexer would contain rules to tell it that the characters `*`, `+`, `^`, `(` and `)` mark the start of a new token, so meaningless tokens like "`12*`" or "`(3`" will not be generated.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The next stage is parsing or syntactic analysis, which is checking that the tokens form an allowable expression.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] This is usually done with reference to a context-free grammar which recursively defines components that can make up an expression and the order in which they must appear.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] However, not all rules defining programming languages can be expressed by context-free grammars alone, for example type validity and proper declaration of identifiers.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] These rules can be formally expressed with attribute grammars.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The final phase is semantic parsing or analysis, which is working out the implications of the expression just validated and taking the appropriate action.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] In the case of a calculator or interpreter, the action is to evaluate the expression or program; a compiler, on the other hand, would generate some kind of code.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Attribute grammars can also be used to define these actions.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The *task* of the parser is essentially to determine if and how the input can be derived from the start symbol of the grammar.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] by expanding all alternative right-hand-sides of grammar rules.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] This is known as the primordial soup approach.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Very similar to sentence diagramming, primordial soup breaks down the constituencies of sentences.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] A parser can start with the input and attempt to rewrite it to the start symbol.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Intuitively, the parser attempts to locate the most basic elements, then the elements containing these, and so on.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] LL parsers and recursive-descent parser are examples of top-down parsers that cannot accommodate left recursive production rules.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Their algorithm is able to produce both left-most and right-most derivations of an input with regard to a given context-free grammar.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] An important distinction with regard to parsers is whether a parser generates a *leftmost derivation* or a *rightmost derivation* (see context-free grammar).
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] LL parsers will generate a leftmost derivation and LR parsers will generate a rightmost derivation (although usually in reverse).
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Some *graphical parsing* algorithms have been designed for visual programming languages.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Parsers for visual languages are sometimes based on graph grammars.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Adaptive parsing algorithms have been used to construct "self-extending" natural language user interfaces.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] A simple parser implementation reads the entire input file, performs an intermediate computation or translation, and then writes the entire output file, such as in-memory multi-pass compilers.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Lookahead establishes the maximum incoming tokens that a parser can use to decide which rule it should use.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Lookahead is especially relevant to LL, LR, and LALR parsers, where it is often explicitly indicated by affixing the lookahead to the algorithm name in parentheses, such as LALR(1).
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Most programming languages, the primary target of parsers, are carefully defined in such a way that a parser with limited lookahead, typically one, can parse them, because parsers with limited lookahead are often more efficient.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] One important change to this trend came in 1990 when Terence Parr created ANTLR for his Ph.D. thesis, a parser generator for efficient LL(*k*) parsers, where *k* is any fixed value.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] LR parsers typically have only a few actions after seeing each token.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] They are shift (add this token to the stack for later reduction), reduce (pop tokens from the stack and form a syntactic construct), end, error (no known rule applies) or conflict (does not know whether to shift or reduce).
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Most programming languages (except for a few such as APL and Smalltalk) and algebraic formulas give higher precedence to multiplication than addition, in which case the correct interpretation of the example above is 1 + (2 * 3).
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Note that Rule4 above is a semantic rule.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] It is possible to rewrite the grammar to incorporate this into the syntax.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] However, not all such rules can be translated into syntax.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Reduces "1" to expression "E" based on rule3.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Shift "+" onto stack from input (in anticipation of rule1).
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Shift "2" onto stack from input (in anticipation of rule3).
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Reduce stack element "2" to Expression "E" based on rule3.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Reduce stack items [E, +, E] and new input "E" to "E" based on rule1.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Shift "*" onto stack from input (in anticipation of rule2).
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Shift "3" onto stack from input (in anticipation of rule3).
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Reduce stack element "3" to expression "E" based on rule3.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Reduce stack items [E, *, E] and new input "E" to "E" based on rule2.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The parse tree and resulting code from it is not correct according to language semantics.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Reduce stack item 1 to simple Expression on input + based on rule3.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The lookahead is +, so we are on path to E +, so we can reduce the stack to E.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Shift + onto stack on input + in anticipation of rule1.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Shift 2 onto stack on input 2 in anticipation of rule3.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Reduce stack item 2 to Expression on input * based on rule3.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The lookahead * expects only E before it.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Now stack has E + E and still the input is *.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] It has two choices now, either to shift based on rule2 or reduction based on rule1.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Since * has higher precedence than + based on rule4, we shift * onto stack in anticipation of rule2.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Shift 3 onto stack on input 3 in anticipation of rule3.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Reduce stack item 3 to Expression after seeing end of input based on rule3.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Reduce stack items E * E to E based on rule2.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] Reduce stack items E + E to E based on rule1.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] The parse tree generated is correct and simply more efficient than non-lookahead parsers.
[src:lxml-xml/parsing] This is the strategy followed in LALR parsers.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] This is a tutorial on XML processing with lxml.etree.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] It briefly overviews the main concepts of the ElementTree API, and some simple enhancements that make your life as a programmer easier.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] For a complete reference of the API, see the generated API documentation.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] To aid in writing portable code, this tutorial makes it clear in the examples which part of the presented API is an extension of lxml.etree over the original ElementTree API.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] An Element is the main container object for the ElementTree API.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Most of the XML tree functionality is accessed through this class.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Elements are organised in an XML tree structure.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] However, this is so common that there is a shorter and much more efficient way to do this: the SubElement factory.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] This is no longer supported as people tend to expect that a "something" evaluates to True and expect Elements to be "something", whether they have children or not.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] So, many users find it surprising that any Element would evaluate to False in an if-statement like the above.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Instead, use len(element), which is both more explicit and less error prone.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] In this example, the last element is *moved* to a different position, instead of being copied, i.e. it is automatically removed from its previous position when it is put in a different place.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Note that in the original ElementTree, a single Element object can sit in any number of places in any number of trees, which allows for the same copy operation as with lists.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] The obvious drawback is that modifications to such an Element will apply to all places where it appears in a tree, which may or may not be intended.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] The upside of this difference is that an Element in lxml.etree always has exactly one parent, which can be queried through the getparent() method.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] This is not supported in the original ElementTree.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Note that attrib is a dict-like object backed by the Element itself.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] This means that any changes to the Element are reflected in attrib and vice versa.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] It also means that the XML tree stays alive in memory as long as the attrib of one of its Elements is in use.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] In many XML documents (*data-centric* documents), this is the only place where text can be found.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] It is encapsulated by a leaf tag at the very bottom of the tree hierarchy.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Here, the <br/> tag is surrounded by text.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] This is often referred to as *document-style* or *mixed-content* XML.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Elements support this through their tail property.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] The two properties .text and .tail are enough to represent any text content in an XML document.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] This way, the ElementTree API does not require any special text nodes in addition to the Element class, that tend to get in the way fairly often (as you might know from classic DOM APIs).
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] However, there are cases where the tail text also gets in the way.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] For example, when you serialise an Element from within the tree, you do not always want its tail text in the result (although you would still want the tail text of its children).
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] If you want to read *only* the text, i.e. without any intermediate tags, you have to recursively concatenate all text and tail attributes in the correct order.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Note that a string result returned by XPath is a special 'smart' object that knows about its origins.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] For problems like the above, where you want to recursively traverse the tree and do something with its elements, tree iteration is a very convenient solution.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Elements provide a tree iterator for this purpose.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] If you know you are only interested in a single tag, you can pass its name to iter() to have it filter for you.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Starting with lxml 3.0, you can also pass more than one tag to intercept on multiple tags during iteration.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] By default, iteration yields all nodes in the tree, including ProcessingInstructions, Comments and Entity instances.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Note that passing a wildcard "*" tag name will also yield all Element nodes (and only elements).
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] In lxml.etree, elements provide further iterators for all directions in the tree: children, parents (or rather ancestors) and siblings.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Serialisation commonly uses the tostring() function that returns a string, or the ElementTree.write() method that writes to a file, a file-like object, or a URL (via FTP PUT or HTTP POST).
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Note that pretty printing appends a newline at the end.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] We therefore use the end='' option here to prevent the print() function from adding another line break.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] In lxml 2.0 and later, as well as in xml.etree, the serialisation functions can do more than XML serialisation.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Here, serialising to a Python text string instead of a byte string might become handy.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] The W3C has a good article about the Unicode character set and character encodings.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] An ElementTree is mainly a document wrapper around a tree with a root node.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] It provides a couple of methods for serialisation and general document handling.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] An ElementTree is also what you get back when you call the parse() function to parse files or file-like objects (see the parsing section below).
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] One of the important differences is that the ElementTree class serialises as a complete document, as opposed to a single Element.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] This serialisation behaviour has changed in lxml 1.3.4.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Before, the tree was serialised without DTD content, which made lxml lose DTD information in an input-output cycle.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] lxml.etree supports parsing XML in a number of ways and from all important sources, namely strings, files, URLs (http/ftp) and file-like objects.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] The main parse functions are fromstring() and parse(), both called with the source as first argument.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] By default, they use the standard parser, but you can always pass a different parser as second argument.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] There is also a corresponding function HTML() for HTML literals.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] The parse() function is used to parse from files and file-like objects.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] As an example of such a file-like object, the following code uses the BytesIO class for reading from a string instead of an external file.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] However, in real life, you would obviously avoid doing this and use the string parsing functions like fromstring() above.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] The reasoning behind this difference is that parse() returns a complete document from a file, while the string parsing functions are commonly used to parse XML fragments.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Note that passing a filename or URL is usually faster than passing an open file or file-like object.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] However, the HTTP/FTP client in libxml2 is rather simple, so things like HTTP authentication require a dedicated URL request library, e.g. urllib2 or requests.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] These libraries usually provide a file-like object for the result that you can parse from while the response is streaming in.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] By default, lxml.etree uses a standard parser with a default setup.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] This creates a parser that removes empty text between tags while parsing, which can reduce the size of the tree and avoid dangling tail text if you know that whitespace-only content is not meaningful for your data.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Note that the whitespace content inside the <b> tag was not removed, as content at leaf elements tends to be data content (even if blank).
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] See help(etree.XMLParser) to find out about the available parser options.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] lxml.etree provides two ways for incremental step-by-step parsing.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] One is through file-like objects, where it calls the read() method repeatedly.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] This is best used where the data arrives from a source like urllib or any other file-like object that can provide data on request.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Here, you can interrupt the parsing process at any time and continue it later on with another call to the feed() method.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] This comes in handy if you want to avoid blocking calls to the parser, e.g. in frameworks like Twisted, or whenever data comes in slowly or in chunks and you want to do other things while waiting for the next chunk.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Note that the text, tail, and children of an Element are not necessarily present yet when receiving the start event.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Only the end event guarantees that the Element has been parsed completely.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] It also allows you to .clear() or modify the content of an Element to save memory.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] So if you parse a large tree and you want to keep memory usage small, you should clean up parts of the tree that you no longer need.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] The keep_tail=True argument to .clear() makes sure that (tail) text content that follows the current element will not be touched.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] It is highly discouraged to modify any content that the parser may not have completely read through yet.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] A very important use case for iterparse() is parsing large generated XML files, e.g. database dumps.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Most often, these XML formats only have one main data item element that hangs directly below the root node and that is repeated thousands of times.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] In this case, it is best practice to let lxml.etree do the tree building and only to intercept on exactly this one Element, using the normal tree API for data extraction.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] If, for some reason, building the tree is not desired at all, the target parser interface of lxml.etree can be used.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] It creates SAX-like events by calling the methods of a target object.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] You can reuse the parser and its target as often as you like, so you should take care that the .close() method really resets the target to a usable state (also in the case of an error!).
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] The notation that ElementTree uses was originally brought up by James Clark.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] It has the major advantage of providing a universally qualified name for a tag, regardless of any prefixes that may or may not have been used or defined in a document.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] By moving the indirection of prefixes out of the way, it makes namespace aware code much clearer and easier to get right.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] As you can see from the example, prefixes only become important when you serialise the result.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] However, the above code looks somewhat verbose due to the lengthy namespace names.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] And retyping or copying a string over and over again is error prone.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] It is therefore common practice to store a namespace URI in a global variable.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Note, however, that this includes all prefixes known in the context of an Element, not only those that it defines itself.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Therefore, modifying the returned dict cannot have any meaningful impact on the Element.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Namespaces on attributes work alike, but as of version 2.3, lxml.etree will ensure that the attribute uses a prefixed namespace declaration.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] This is because unprefixed attribute names are not considered being in a namespace by the XML namespace specification (section 6.2), so they may end up losing their namespace on a serialise-parse roundtrip, even if they appear in a namespaced element.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] One such example is the module lxml.html.builder, which provides a vocabulary for HTML.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] When dealing with multiple namespaces, it is good practice to define one ElementMaker for each namespace URI.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Again, note how the above example predefines the tag builders in named constants.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] That makes it easy to put all tag declarations of a namespace into one Python module and to import/use the tag name constants from there.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] This avoids pitfalls like typos or accidentally missing namespaces.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] The ElementTree library comes with a simple XPath-like path language called ElementPath.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] The main difference is that you can use the {namespace}tag notation in ElementPath expressions.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] However, advanced features like value comparison and functions are not available.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] In addition to a full XPath implementation, lxml.etree supports the ElementPath language in the same way ElementTree does, even using (almost) the same implementation.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] As long as the tree is not modified, this path expression represents an identifier for a given element that can be used to find() it in the same tree later.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Compared to XPath, ElementPath expressions have the advantage of being self-contained even for documents that use namespaces.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] The .iter() method is a special case that only finds specific tags in the tree by their name, not based on a path.
[src:lxml-xml/tutorial] Note that the .find() method simply returns None if no match is found, whereas the other two examples would raise a StopIteration exception.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] A simple example would be to consider an XML instance that contained references to a customer and an ordered product.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] Both the customer element and the product element could have a child element named **id**.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] References to the **id** element would therefore be ambiguous; placing them in different namespaces would remove the ambiguity.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] A *namespace name* is a uniform resource identifier (URI).
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] Typically, the URI chosen for the namespace of a given XML vocabulary describes a resource under the control of the author or organization defining the vocabulary, such as a URL for the author's Web server.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] However, the namespace specification does not require nor suggest that the namespace URI be used to retrieve information; it is simply treated by an XML parser as a string.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] For example, the document at http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml itself does not contain any code.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] It simply describes the XHTML namespace to human readers.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] Using a URI (such as "http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml") to identify a namespace, rather than a simple string (such as "xhtml"), reduces the probability of different namespaces using duplicate identifiers.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] Although the term *namespace URI* is widespread, the W3C Recommendation refers to it as the *namespace name*.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] The specification is not entirely prescriptive about the precise rules for namespace names (it does not explicitly say that parsers must reject documents where the namespace name is not a valid Uniform Resource Identifier), and many XML parsers allow any character string to be used.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] In version 1.1 of the recommendation, the namespace name becomes an Internationalized Resource Identifier, which licenses the use of non-ASCII characters that in practice were already accepted by nearly all XML software.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] The term *namespace URI* persists, however, not only in popular usage, but also in many other specifications from W3C and elsewhere.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] The result of the debate was a ruling from W3C that relative URIs were deprecated.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] The use of URIs taking the form of URLs in the http scheme (such as *http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml*) is common, despite the absence of any formal relationship with the HTTP protocol.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] The Namespaces specification does not say what should happen if such a URL is dereferenced (that is, if software attempts to retrieve a document from this location).
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] One convention adopted by some users is to place an RDDL document at the location.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] In general, however, users should assume that the namespace URI is simply a name, not the address of a document on the Web.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] An XML namespace is declared using the reserved XML attribute `xmlns` or `xmlns:*prefix*`, the value of which must be a valid namespace name.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] Any element or attribute whose name starts with the prefix "xhtml:" is considered to be in the XHTML namespace, if it or an ancestor has the above namespace declaration.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] It is also possible to declare a default namespace.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] In this case, any element without a namespace prefix is considered to be in the XHTML namespace, if it or an ancestor has the above default namespace declaration.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] If there is no default namespace declaration in scope, the namespace name has no value.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] In that case, an element without an explicit namespace prefix is considered not to be in any namespace.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] Attributes are never subject to the default namespace.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] An attribute without an explicit namespace prefix is considered not to be in any namespace.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] Different specifications have taken different approaches on how namespace information is presented to applications.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] Nearly all programming models allow the name of an element or attribute node to be retrieved as a three-part name: the local name, the namespace prefix, and the namespace URI.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] Applications should avoid attaching any significance to the choice of prefix, but the information is provided because it can be helpful to human readers.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] Names are considered equal if the namespace URI and local name match.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] In addition, most models provide some way of determining which namespaces have been declared for a given element.
[src:lxml-xml/xml-namespace] This information is needed because some XML vocabularies allow qualified names (containing namespace prefixes) to appear in the content of elements or attributes, as well as in their names.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The design goals of XML emphasize simplicity, generality, and usability across the Internet.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] It is a textual data format with strong support via Unicode for different human languages.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Although the design of XML focuses on documents, the language is widely used for the representation of arbitrary data structures, such as those used in web services.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Several schema systems exist to aid in the definition of XML-based languages, while programmers have developed many application programming interfaces (APIs) to aid the processing of XML data.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The main purpose of XML is serialization, i.e. storing, transmitting, and reconstructing arbitrary data.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] For two disparate systems to exchange information, they need to agree upon a file format.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] It is therefore analogous to a lingua franca for representing information.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] As a markup language, XML labels, categorizes, and structurally organizes information.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XML tags represent the data structure and contain metadata.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] What is within the tags is data, encoded in the way the XML standard specifies.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] An additional XML schema (XSD) defines the necessary metadata for interpreting and validating XML.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] (This is also referred to as the canonical schema.) An XML document that adheres to basic XML rules is "well-formed"; one that adheres to its schema is "valid".
[src:lxml-xml/xml] IETF RFC 7303 (which supersedes the older RFC 3023), provides rules for the construction of media types for use in XML message.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] It defines three media types: `application/xml` (`text/xml` is an alias), `application/xml-external-parsed-entity` (`text/xml-external-parsed-entity` is an alias) and `application/xml-dtd`.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] They are used for transmitting raw XML files without exposing their internal semantics.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] RFC 7303 further recommends that XML-based languages be given media types ending in `+xml`, for example, `image/svg+xml` for SVG.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Further guidelines for the use of XML in a networked context appear in RFC 3470, also known as IETF BCP 70, a document covering many aspects of designing and deploying an XML-based language.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XML has come into common use for the interchange of data over the Internet.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Hundreds of document formats using XML syntax have been developed, including RSS, Atom, Office Open XML, OpenDocument, SVG, COLLADA, and XHTML.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XML also provides the base language for communication protocols such as SOAP and XMPP.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] It is one of the message exchange formats used in the Asynchronous JavaScript and XML (AJAX) programming technique.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Many industry data standards, such as Health Level 7, OpenTravel Alliance, FpML, MISMO, and the National Information Exchange Model are based on XML and the rich features of the XML schema specification.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] In publishing, Darwin Information Typing Architecture is an XML industry data standard.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XML is used extensively to underpin various publishing formats.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] One of the applications of XML in science is the representation of operational meteorology information based on IWXXM standards.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The material in this section is based on the XML Specification.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] This is not an exhaustive list of all the constructs that appear in XML; it provides an introduction to the key constructs most often encountered in day-to-day use.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] character (except Null) may appear in an (1.1) XML document (while some are discouraged).
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The specification places requirements on what an XML processor must do and not do, but the application is outside its scope.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Strings of characters that are not markup are content.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] are classified as markup, while the text between them is classified as content.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] In addition, whitespace before and after the outermost element is classified as markup.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] is a logical document component that either begins with a start-tag and ends with a matching end-tag or consists only of an empty-element tag.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] that exists within a start-tag or empty-element tag.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] , where the names of the attributes are "src" and "alt", and their values are "madonna.jpg" and "Madonna" respectively.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] , where the name of the attribute is "number" and its value is "3".
[src:lxml-xml/xml] An XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] with some format beyond what XML defines itself.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] that describes some information about themselves.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XML documents consist entirely of characters from the Unicode repertoire.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Except for a small number of specifically excluded control characters, any character defined by Unicode may appear within the content of an XML document.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XML includes facilities for identifying the *encoding* of the Unicode characters that make up the document, and for expressing characters that, for one reason or another, cannot be used directly.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XML 1.1 extends the set of allowed characters to include all the above, plus the remaining characters in the range U+0001–U+001F.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] At the same time, however, it restricts the use of C0 and C1 control characters other than U+0009 (Horizontal Tab), U+000A (Line Feed), U+000D (Carriage Return), and U+0085 (Next Line) by requiring them to be written in escaped form (for example U+0001 must be written as `&#x01;` or its equivalent).
[src:lxml-xml/xml] In the case of C1 characters, this restriction is a backwards incompatibility; it was introduced to allow common encoding errors to be detected.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The code point U+0000 (Null) is the only character that is not permitted in any XML 1.1 document.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The Unicode character set can be encoded into bytes for storage or transmission in a variety of different ways, called "encodings".
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Unicode itself defines encodings that cover the entire repertoire; well-known ones include UTF-8 (which the XML standard recommends using, without a BOM) and UTF-16.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] There are many other text encodings that predate Unicode, such as ASCII and various ISO/IEC 8859; their character repertoires are in every case subsets of the Unicode character set.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XML allows the use of any of the Unicode-defined encodings and any other encodings whose characters also appear in Unicode.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XML also provides a mechanism whereby an XML processor can reliably, without any prior knowledge, determine which encoding is being used.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Encodings other than UTF-8 and UTF-16 are not necessarily recognized by every XML parser (and in some cases not even UTF-16, even though the standard mandates it to also be recognized).
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XML provides *escape* facilities for including characters that are problematic to include directly.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] All permitted Unicode characters may be represented with a *numeric character reference*.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Consider the Chinese character "中", whose numeric code in Unicode is hexadecimal 4E2D, or decimal 20,013.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] A user whose keyboard offers no method for entering this character could still insert it in an XML document encoded either as `&#20013;` or `&#x4e2d;`.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Similarly, the string "I <3 Jörg" could be encoded for inclusion in an XML document as `I &lt;3 J&#xF6;rg`.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] `&#0;` is not permitted because the null character is one of the control characters excluded from XML, even when using a numeric character reference.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] An alternative encoding mechanism such as Base64 is needed to represent such characters.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Comments may appear anywhere in a document outside other markup.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Comments cannot appear before the XML declaration.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Comments begin with `<!--` and end with `-->`.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] For compatibility with SGML, the string "--" (double-hyphen) is not allowed inside comments; this means comments cannot be nested.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The ampersand has no special significance within comments, so entity and character references are not recognized as such, and there is no way to represent characters outside the character set of the document encoding.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XML 1.0 (Fifth Edition) and XML 1.1 support the direct use of almost any Unicode character in element names, attributes, comments, character data, and processing instructions (other than the ones that have special symbolic meaning in XML itself, such as the less-than sign, "<").
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The XML specification defines an XML document as a well-formed text, meaning that it satisfies a list of syntax rules provided in the specification.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The definition of an XML document excludes texts that contain violations of well-formedness rules; they are simply not XML.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] An XML processor that encounters such a violation is required to report such errors and to cease normal processing.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] This policy, occasionally referred to as "draconian error handling", stands in notable contrast to the behavior of programs that process HTML, which are designed to produce a reasonable result even in the presence of severe markup errors.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XML's policy in this area has been criticized as a violation of Postel's law ("Be conservative in what you send; be liberal in what you accept").
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The XML specification defines a valid XML document as a well-formed XML document which also conforms to the rules of a Document Type Definition (DTD).
[src:lxml-xml/xml] In addition to being well formed, an XML document may be *valid*.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] This means that it contains a reference to a Document Type Definition (DTD), and that its elements and attributes are declared in that DTD and follow the grammatical rules for them that the DTD specifies.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XML processors are classified as *validating* or *non-validating* depending on whether or not they check XML documents for validity.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] A processor that discovers a validity error must be able to report it, but may continue normal processing.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] A DTD is an example of a *schema* or *grammar*.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Since the initial publication of XML 1.0, there has been substantial work in the area of schema languages for XML.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Such schema languages typically constrain the set of elements that may be used in a document, which attributes may be applied to them, the order in which they may appear, and the allowable parent/child relationships.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The oldest schema language for XML is the document type definition (DTD), inherited from SGML.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] DTD technology is still used in many applications because of its ubiquity.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] A newer schema language, described by the W3C as the successor of DTDs, is XML Schema, often referred to by the initialism for XML Schema instances, XSD (XML Schema Definition).
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XSDs are far more powerful than DTDs in describing XML languages.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] They use a rich datatyping system and allow for more detailed constraints on an XML document's logical structure.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XSDs also use an XML-based format, which makes it possible to use ordinary XML tools to help process them.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] RELAX NG (Regular Language for XML Next Generation) was initially specified by OASIS and is now a standard (Part 2: *Regular-grammar-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:lxml-xml/xml] RELAX NG schemas may be written in either an XML based syntax or a more compact non-XML syntax; the two syntaxes are isomorphic and James Clark's conversion tool—Trang—can convert between them without loss of information.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] RELAX NG has a simpler definition and validation framework than XML Schema, making it easier to use and implement.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] It also has the ability to use datatype framework plug-ins; a RELAX NG schema author, for example, can require values in an XML document to conform to definitions in XML Schema Datatypes.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Schematron is a language for making assertions about the presence or absence of patterns in an XML document.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Schematron is now a standard (Part 3: *Rule-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:lxml-xml/xml] DSDL (Document Schema Definition Languages) is a multi-part ISO/IEC standard (ISO/IEC 19757) that brings together a comprehensive set of small schema languages, each targeted at specific problems.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] DSDL includes RELAX NG full and compact syntax, Schematron assertion language, and languages for defining datatypes, character repertoire constraints, renaming and entity expansion, and namespace-based routing of document fragments to different validators.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] DSDL schema languages do not have the vendor support of XML Schemas yet, and are to some extent a grassroots reaction of industrial publishers to the lack of utility of XML Schemas for publishing.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Some schema languages not only describe the structure of a particular XML format but also offer limited facilities to influence processing of individual XML files that conform to this format.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] DTDs and XSDs both have this ability; they can for instance provide the infoset augmentation facility and attribute defaults.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] RELAX NG and Schematron intentionally do not provide these.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] A cluster of specifications closely related to XML have been developed, starting soon after the initial publication of XML 1.0.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] It is frequently the case that the term "XML" is used to refer to XML together with one or more of these other technologies that have come to be seen as part of the XML core.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Some other specifications conceived as part of the "XML Core" have failed to find wide adoption, including XInclude, XLink, and XPointer.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The design goals of XML include, "It shall be easy to write programs which process XML documents." Despite this, the XML specification contains almost no information about how programmers might go about doing such processing.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The XML Infoset specification provides a vocabulary to refer to the constructs within an XML document, but does not provide any guidance on how to access this information.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] A variety of APIs for accessing XML have been developed and used, and some have been standardized.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Stream-oriented facilities require less memory and, for certain tasks based on a linear traversal of an XML document, are faster and simpler than other alternatives.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Tree-traversal and data-binding APIs typically require the use of much more memory, but are often found more convenient for use by programmers; some include declarative retrieval of document components via the use of XPath expressions.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XSLT is designed for declarative description of XML document transformations, and has been widely implemented both in server-side packages and Web browsers.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XQuery overlaps XSLT in its functionality, but is designed more for searching of large XML databases.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Simple API for XML (SAX) is a lexical, event-driven API in which a document is read serially and its contents are reported as callbacks to various methods on a handler object of the user's design.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] SAX is fast and efficient to implement, but difficult to use for extracting information at random from the XML, since it tends to burden the application author with keeping track of what part of the document is being processed.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] It is better suited to situations in which certain types of information are always handled the same way, no matter where they occur in the document.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Pull parsing treats the document as a series of items read in sequence using the iterator design pattern.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] A pull parser creates an iterator that sequentially visits the various elements, attributes, and data in an XML document.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Code that uses this iterator can test the current item (to tell, for example, whether it is a start-tag or end-tag, or text), and inspect its attributes (local name, namespace, values of XML attributes, value of text, etc.), and can also move the iterator to the next item.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The code can thus extract information from the document as it traverses it.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The recursive-descent approach tends to lend itself to keeping data as typed local variables in the code doing the parsing, while SAX, for instance, typically requires a parser to manually maintain intermediate data within a stack of elements that are parent elements of the element being parsed.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Pull-parsing code can be more straightforward to understand and maintain than SAX parsing code.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The Document Object Model (DOM) is an interface that allows for navigation of the entire document as if it were a tree of node objects representing the document's contents.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] A DOM document can be created by a parser, or can be generated manually by users (with limitations).
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Data types in DOM nodes are abstract; implementations provide their own programming language-specific bindings.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] DOM implementations tend to be memory intensive, as they generally require the entire document to be loaded into memory and constructed as a tree of objects before access is allowed.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XML data binding is a technique for simplifying development of applications that need to work with XML documents.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] It involves mapping the XML document to a hierarchy of strongly typed objects, rather than using the generic objects created by a DOM parser.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The resulting code is often easier to read and maintain, and it can help to identify problems at compile time rather than run-time.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XML data binding is particularly well-suited for applications where the document structure is known and fixed at the time the application is written.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] By creating a strongly typed representation of the XML data, developers can take advantage of modern integrated development environments (IDEs) that provide features like auto-complete, code refactoring, and code highlighting.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] This can make it easier to write correct and efficient code, and reduce the risk of errors and bugs.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Example data-binding systems include the Java Architecture for XML Binding (JAXB), XML Serialization in .NET Framework, and XML serialization in gSOAP.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XML has appeared as a first-class data type in other languages.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The ECMAScript for XML (E4X) extension to the ECMAScript/JavaScript language explicitly defines two specific objects (XML and XMLList) for JavaScript, which support XML document nodes and XML node lists as distinct objects and use a dot-notation specifying parent-child relationships.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] E4X is supported by the Mozilla 2.5+ browsers (though now deprecated) and Adobe Actionscript but has not been widely adopted.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Similar notations are used in Microsoft's LINQ implementation for Microsoft .NET 3.5 and above, and in Scala (which uses the Java VM).
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The open-source xmlsh application, which provides a Linux-like shell with special features for XML manipulation, similarly treats XML as a data type, using the <[ ]> notation.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The Resource Description Framework defines a data type `rdf:XMLLiteral` to hold wrapped, canonical XML.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Facebook has produced extensions to the PHP and JavaScript languages that add XML to the core syntax in a similar fashion to E4X, namely XHP and JSX respectively.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XML is an application profile of SGML (ISO 8879).
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The versatility of SGML for dynamic information display was understood by early digital media publishers in the late 1980s prior to the rise of the Internet.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] By the mid-1990s some practitioners of SGML had gained experience with the then-new World Wide Web, and believed that SGML offered solutions to some of the problems the Web was likely to face as it grew.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Dan Connolly added SGML to the list of W3C's activities when he joined the staff in 1995; work began in mid-1996 when Sun Microsystems engineer Jon Bosak developed a charter and recruited collaborators.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Bosak was well-connected in the small community of people who had experience both in SGML and the Web.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] XML was compiled by a working group of eleven members, supported by a (roughly) 150-member Interest Group.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Technical debate took place on the Interest Group mailing list and issues were resolved by consensus or, when that failed, majority vote of the Working Group.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] A record of design decisions and their rationales was compiled by Michael Sperberg-McQueen on December 4, 1997.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] James Clark served as Technical Lead of the Working Group, notably contributing the empty-element `<empty />` syntax and the name "XML".
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Other names that had been put forward for consideration included "MAGMA" (Minimal Architecture for Generalized Markup Applications), "SLIM" (Structured Language for Internet Markup) and "MGML" (Minimal Generalized Markup Language).
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The co-editors of the specification were originally Tim Bray and Michael Sperberg-McQueen.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Halfway through the project, Bray accepted a consulting engagement with Netscape, provoking vociferous protests from Microsoft.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Bray was temporarily asked to resign the editorship.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] This led to intense dispute in the Working Group, eventually solved by the appointment of Microsoft's Jean Paoli as a third co-editor.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The XML Working Group communicated primarily through email and weekly teleconferences.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] The major design decisions were reached in a short burst of intense work between August and November 1996, when the first Working Draft of an XML specification was published.
[src:lxml-xml/xml] Further design work continued through 1997, and XML 1.0 became a W3C Recommendation on February 10, 1998.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] The XPath language is based on a tree representation of the XML document, and provides the ability to navigate around the tree, selecting nodes by a variety of criteria.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] In popular use (though not in the official specification), an XPath expression is often referred to simply as "an XPath".
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] Originally motivated by a desire to provide a common syntax and behavior model between XPointer and XSLT, subsets of the XPath query language are used in other W3C specifications such as XML Schema, XForms and the Internationalization Tag Set (ITS).
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] XPath has been adopted by a number of XML processing libraries and tools, many of which also offer CSS Selectors, another W3C standard, as a simpler alternative to XPath.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] There are several versions of XPath in use.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] However, XPath 1.0 is still the version that is most widely available.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] The most important kind of expression in XPath is a *location path*.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] A location path consists of a sequence of *location steps*.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] An XPath expression is evaluated with respect to a *context node*.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] An Axis Specifier such as 'child' or 'descendant' specifies the direction to navigate from the context node.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] The node test and the predicate are used to filter the nodes specified by the axis specifier: For example, the node test 'A' requires that all nodes navigated to must have label 'A'.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] A predicate can be used to specify that the selected nodes have certain properties, which are specified by XPath expressions themselves.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] The XPath syntax comes in two flavors: the *abbreviated syntax*, is more compact and allows XPaths to be written and read easily using intuitive and, in many cases, familiar characters and constructs.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] The *full syntax* is more verbose, but allows for more options to be specified, and is more descriptive if read carefully.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] The compact notation allows many defaults and abbreviations for common cases.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] that selects C elements that are children of B elements that are children of the A element that forms the outermost element of the XML document.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] The XPath syntax is designed to mimic URI (Uniform Resource Identifier) and Unix-style file path syntax.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] More complex expressions can be constructed by specifying an axis other than the default 'child' axis, a node test other than a simple name, or predicates, which can be written in square brackets after any step.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] selects the first child ('`*[1]`'), whatever its name, of every B element that itself is a child or other, deeper descendant ('`//`') of an A element that is a child of the current context node (the expression does not begin with a '`/`').
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] The predicate `[1]` binds more tightly than the `/` operator.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] To select the first node selected by the expression `A//B/*`, write `(A//B/*)[1]`.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] Note also, index values in XPath predicates (technically, 'proximity positions' of XPath node sets) start from 1, not 0 as common in languages like C and Java.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] Here, in each step of the XPath, the **axis** (e.g.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] `child` or `descendant-or-self`) is explicitly specified, followed by `::` and then the **node test**, such as `A` or `node()` in the examples above.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] Axis specifiers indicate navigation direction within the tree representation of the XML document.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] As an example of using the **attribute** axis in abbreviated syntax, `//a/@href` selects the attribute called `href` in `a` elements anywhere in the document tree.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] The expression **.** (an abbreviation for **self::node()**) is most commonly used within a predicate to refer to the currently selected node.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] For example, `h3[.='See also']` selects an element called `h3` in the current context, whose text content is `See also`.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] Node tests may consist of specific node names or more general expressions.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] In the case of an XML document in which the namespace prefix `gs` has been defined, `//gs:enquiry` will find all the `enquiry` elements in that namespace, and `//gs:*` will find all elements, regardless of local name, in that namespace.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] Predicates, written as expressions in square brackets, can be used to filter a node-set according to some condition.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] For example, `a` returns a node-set (all the `a` elements which are children of the context node), and `a[@href='help.php']` keeps only those elements having an `href` attribute with the value `help.php`.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] There is no limit to the number of predicates in a step, and they need not be confined to the last step in an XPath.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] Paths specified in predicates begin at the context of the current step (i.e. that of the immediately preceding node test) and do not alter that context.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] All predicates must be satisfied for a match to occur.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] When the value of the predicate is numeric, it is syntactic-sugar for comparing against the node's position in the node-set (as given by the function `position()`).
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] So `p[1]` is shorthand for `p[position()=1]` and selects the first `p` element child, while `p[last()]` is shorthand for `p[position()=last()]` and selects the last `p` child of the context node.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] In other cases, the value of the predicate is automatically converted to a Boolean.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] When the predicate evaluates to a node-set, the result is true when the node-set is non-empty.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] Thus `p[@x]` selects those `p` elements that have an attribute named `x`.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] The reference to an attribute of the top-level element in the first predicate affects neither the context of other predicates nor that of the location step itself.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] Predicate order is significant if predicates test the position of a node.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] Each predicate takes a node-set returns a (potentially) smaller node-set.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] So `a[1][@href='help.php']` will find a match only if the first `a` child of the context node satisfies the condition `@href='help.php'`, while `a[@href='help.php'][1]` will find the first `a` child that satisfies this condition.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] XPath 1.0 defines four data types: node-sets (sets of nodes with no intrinsic order), strings, numbers and Booleans.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] Some of the more commonly useful functions are detailed below.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] returns a number representing the position of this node in the sequence of nodes currently being processed (for example, the nodes selected by an xsl:for-each instruction in XSLT).
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] returns the number of nodes in the node-set supplied as its argument.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] converts any of the four XPath data types into a string according to built-in rules.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] If the value of the argument is a node-set, the function returns the string-value of the first node in document order, ignoring any further nodes.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] is removed and any sequences of whitespace characters are replaced by a single space.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] formatted, which could make further string processing unreliable.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] converts the string values of all the nodes found by the XPath argument into numbers, according to the built-in casting rules, then returns the sum of these numbers.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] Expressions can be created inside predicates using the operators: `=, !=, <=, <, >=` and `>`.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] Boolean expressions may be combined with brackets `()` and the Boolean operators `and` and `or` as well as the `not()` function described above.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] Numeric calculations can use `*, +, -, div` and `mod`.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] Strings can consist of any Unicode characters.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] `//item[@price > 2*@discount]` selects items whose price attribute is greater than twice the numeric value of their discount attribute.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] Entire node-sets can be combined ('unioned') using the vertical bar character |.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] Node sets that meet one or more of several conditions can be found by combining the conditions inside a predicate with '`or`'.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] `v[x or y] | w[z]` will return a single node-set consisting of all the `v` elements that have `x` or `y` child-elements, as well as all the `w` elements that have `z` child-elements, that were found in the current context.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] selects addresses of all English Wikimedia projects (text of all `edition` elements where `language` attribute is equal to *English*).
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] selects addresses of all Wikipedias (text of all `edition` elements that exist under `project` element with a name attribute of *Wikipedia*).
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] The Java package **`javax.xml.xpath`** has been part of Java standard edition since Java 5 via the Java API for XML Processing.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] Technically this is an XPath API rather than an XPath implementation, and it allows the programmer the ability to select a specific implementation that conforms to the interface.
[src:lxml-xml/xpath] XPath is increasingly used to express constraints in schema languages for XML.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] XSLT 3.0 implementations support Java, .NET, C/C++, Python, PHP and NodeJS.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] An XSLT 3.0 JavaScript library can also be hosted within the web browser.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] Modern web browsers also include native support for XSLT 1.0.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] XSLT has become obsolete in the browser due to better technologies.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] Google Chrome will remove its XSLT implementation to make the browser more secure.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] The XSLT document transformation specifies how to transform an XML document into new document (usually XML, but other formats, such as plain text are supported).
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] Typically, input documents are XML files, but anything from which the processor can build an XQuery and XPath Data Model can be used, such as relational database tables or geographical information systems.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] While XSLT was originally designed as a special-purpose language for XML transformation, the language is Turing-complete, making it theoretically capable of arbitrary computations.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] XSLT is influenced by functional languages, and by text-based pattern matching languages like SNOBOL and AWK.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] Its most direct predecessor is DSSSL, which did for SGML what XSLT does for XML.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] The XSLT processor takes one or more XML source documents, plus one or more XSLT stylesheets, and processes them to produce one or multiple output documents.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] In contrast to widely implemented imperative programming languages like C, XSLT is declarative.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] The basic processing paradigm is pattern matching.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] First, assuming a stylesheet has already been read and prepared, the processor builds a source tree from the input XML document.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] It then processes the source tree's root node, finds the best-matching template for that node in the stylesheet, and evaluates the template's contents.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] Instructions in each template generally direct the processor to either create nodes in the result tree, or to process more nodes in the source tree in the same way as the root node.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] Finally the result tree is serialized as XML or HTML text.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] XSLT uses XPath to identify subsets of the source document tree and perform calculations.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] XPath also provides a range of functions, which XSLT itself further augments.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] XSLT 1.0 uses XPath 1.0, while XSLT 2.0 uses XPath 2.0.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] XSLT 3.0 will work with either XPath 3.0 or 3.1.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] In the case of 1.0 and 2.0, the XSLT and XPath specifications were published on the same date.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] With 3.0, however, they were no longer synchronized; XPath 3.0 became a Recommendation in April 2014, followed by XPath 3.1 in February 2017; XSLT 3.0 followed in June 2017.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] XSLT functionalities overlap with those of XQuery, which was initially conceived as a query language for large collections of XML documents.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] The XSLT 2.0 and XQuery 1.0 standards were developed by separate working groups within W3C, working together to ensure a common approach where appropriate.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] They share the same data model, type system, and function library, and both include XPath 2.0 as a sublanguage.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] The two languages, however, are rooted in different traditions and serve the needs of different communities.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] XSLT was primarily conceived as a stylesheet language whose primary goal was to render XML for the human reader on screen, on the web (as a web template language), or on paper.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] XQuery was primarily conceived as a database query language in the tradition of SQL.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] Because the two languages originate in different communities, XSLT is stronger in its handling of narrative documents with more flexible structure, while XQuery is stronger in its data handling, for example when performing relational joins.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] The `<output>` element can optionally take the attribute `media-type`, which allows one to set the media type (or MIME type) for the resulting output, for example: `<xsl:output output="xml" media-type="application/xml"/>`.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] The XSLT 1.0 recommendation recommends the more general attribute types `text/xml` and `application/xml` since for a long time there was no registered media type for XSLT.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] During this time `text/xsl` became the de facto standard.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] In XSLT 1.0 it was not specified how the `media-type` values should be used.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] With the release of the XSLT 2.0, the W3C recommended in 2007 the registration of the MIME media type `application/xslt+xml` and it was later registered with the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] Pre-1.0 working drafts of XSLT used `text/xsl` in their embedding examples, and this type was implemented and continued to be promoted by Microsoft in Internet Explorer and MSXML circa 2012.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] It is also widely recognized in the `xml-stylesheet` processing instruction by other browsers.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] In practice, therefore, users wanting to control transformation in the browser using this processing instruction were obliged to use this unregistered media type.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] This XHTML generates the output below when rendered in a web browser.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] In order for a web browser to be able to apply an XSL transformation to an XML document on display, an XML stylesheet processing instruction can be inserted into XML.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] In this example, `text/xsl` is technically incorrect according to the W3C specifications (which say the type should be `application/xslt+xml`), but it is the only media type that is widely supported across browsers as of 2009, and the situation is unchanged in 2021.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] Most early XSLT processors were interpreters.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] More recently, code generation is increasingly common, using portable intermediate languages (such as Java bytecode or .NET Common Intermediate Language) as the target.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] However, even the interpretive products generally offer separate analysis and execution phases, allowing an optimized expression tree to be created in memory and reused to perform multiple transformations.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] This gives substantial performance benefits in online publishing applications, where the same transformation is applied many times per second to different source documents.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] This separation is reflected in the design of XSLT processing APIs (such as JAXP).
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] Early XSLT processors had very few optimizations.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] Stylesheet documents were read into Document Object Models and the processor would act on them directly.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] Many processors also use tree representations that are significantly more efficient (in both space and time) than general-purpose DOM implementations.
[src:lxml-xml/xslt] In June 2014, Debbie Lockett and Michael Kay introduced an open-source benchmarking framework for XSLT processors called XT-Speedo.
